definition.value: A chromium group element atom that has atomic number 24.
A member of the class of rifamycins that is a a semisynthetic antibiotic derived from Amycolatopsis rifamycinica (previously known as Amycolatopsis mediterranei and Streptomyces mediterranei).
A monochlorophenol substituted at the pare position by a chlorine atom.
A hexadienedioate compound having a 2-hydroxy substituent.
The beta-isomer of mannobiose.
A monosaccharide derivative that consists of gossypetin substituted by a 6-deoxy-alpha-L-mannopyranosyl moiety at position 8 via a glycosidic linkage.

A polydisperse, highly branched glucan composed of chains of D-glucopyranose residues in alpha(1->4) glycosidic linkage, joined together by alpha(1->6) glycosidic linkages. A small number of alpha(1->3) glycosidic linkages and some cumulative alpha(1->6) links also may occur. The branches in glycogen typically contain 8 to 12 glucose residues.
A 7-hydroxyisoflavone with additional hydroxy groups at positions 5 and 4'. It is a phytoestrogenic isoflavone with antioxidant properties.
An L-tyrosine derivative obtained by replacement of one of the amino hydrogen by a hydroxy group.
An anthocyanidin cation that is cyanidin substituted by a hydroxy group at position 6.
A member of the class of  naphthaldehydes that is naphthalene-2-carbaldehyde substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1.
A nitrile that is L-glutamine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the amide nitrogen is replaced by a 2-cyanoethyl group.
A bornane monoterpenoid that is 1,7,7-trimethylbicyclo[2.2.1]heptane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2.
A 1,6-dicarboxylic acid compound having an amino substituent at the 2-position and an oxo substituent at the 3-position.
The simplest member of the class of monochlorobenzenes, that is benzene in which a single hydrogen has been substituted by a chlorine.
An alpha-D-glucan in which the glucose units are connected by (1->3) linkages.

A glucan composed of unbranched chains of D-glucopyranose residues in alpha(1->4) glycosidic linkage. The number of repeated glucose subunits (n) is usually in the range of 300 to 3000, but can be many thousands. One of the two components of starch (the other, 70-80%, being amylopectin). Cf. linear maltodextrin, in which the chain length is typically between 3 and 17 glucose units.
A trihydroxyflavanone in which the three hydroxy substituents are located at positions 3, 5 and 7.
The conjugate base of loracarbef.
A member of the class of chalcones that is trans-chalcone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 4, 2' and 4' and a prenyl group at position 3'.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion resulting from the removal of a proton from both of the carboxylic acid groups of 2-isopropylmalic acid.
Chemical element (nickel group element atom) with atomic number 28.
A 3beta-sterol formed from lanosterol by reduction across the C-24-C-25 double bond.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is 2-oxopentanoic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a carbamimidamido group.
A monosaccharide derivative that is (+)-catechin substituted by a beta-D-xylopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
